      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Park to Stir Me, and Soothe You</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steven Cohen letter says compromise should be reached so that Central Park can accomodate both lovers of noise and of quiet (May 29 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Central Park Keepers Struggling to Balance Masses With Grasses'' (front page, May 29):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Central Park Keepers Struggling to Balance Masses With Grasses'' (front page, May 29):</p>
        <p>Adam Kaufman, a Central Park Conservancy official, says: ''We've made the park beautiful. Now we want to make it beautiful to all the senses, including hearing.'' But the ugly assault on our ears comes not from the music he wants to curb but from cars. Cars should be banned from the loop to restore Central Park to its original purpose as a refuge from the noise of the city.</p>
        <p>FRANK TODISCO  New York, May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
